<br>
I think a better question is: Please explain what these great benefits are that will help society. You are the ones asking us to change societal rules so I believe the burden is on you. This is the problem when liberal and conservative values colide. On one hand we have tradition and on the other is change. Society has its traditions and sometimes they grow outdated and should be changed if the majority agree. But &quot;Queer eye for the straight guy&quot; being a big hit on cable's Bravo channel or Ellen Degeneras &quot;coming out&quot; on network TV does not equal a majority shift in traditional thinking.<br>
<br>
<br>
&quot;Please explain why &quot;traditional&quot; marriage is such an integral part of society.&quot;<br>
<br>
Yeah, why is anything traditional worth doing? I've been thinking about this the last couple days. I'd like to think I'm not very traditional, but then again I don't want to use a unisex bathroom if I have a choice. I like driving on the right hand side of the road. And I don't want to be introduced to another guy as someone's &quot;wife&quot;. I've been programmed against it. Sorry.<br>
<br>
I wondered what I would think if a minority of the population wanted to do away with all men and women's restrooms and make them all unisex. Or if a movement started to make medical alternatives available to allow men to become pregnent and carry a baby to term, along with making insurance carriers provide coverage. What happens when sex change operations are considered normal medical procedure and are covered by insurance? Will society be ruined? Will it be different and will I want to live there?<br>
<br>
This is all speculation, of course, and it may enlighten and advance our society beyond measure, or it may bring our entire system crashing down. I don't know. But the important thing is you are asking us to speculate when you ask &quot;why not?&quot;, and then when we do you dismiss it as a slippery slope, conjecture, and speculation. But when we ask you to list the benefits all we get is: It hurts no one. I wish I could agree with you. You don't no who it will hurt because the change hasn't been implemented. All I know is I like things as they are, and you haven't convinced me that change is worth the effort. If you don't think releasing restrictions on regulations like marrige will not help poligamists or incest supports in our common law system, you are more of an optimist than me.  <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#4D4D4D><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub101.ezboard.com/bthetribunaldotorg.showUserPublicProfile?gid=loeganwolfheart>Loegan Wolfheart</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Please do things my way, thx.</span><br>  Posts: 3735<br> <font color=#FFFFFF>(8/6/03 2:33 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub101.ezboard.com/fthetribunaldotorgfrm36.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=811.topic&index=246>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://loegan.homestead.com/files/rn.jpg WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: ...</span><hr size=1> <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>I think a better question is: Please explain what these great benefits are that will help society. </em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--><br>
<br>
Anytime society shows fairness, I call that a plus. And yes, I honestly believe this is about fairness, not some massive conspiracy to destroy marriage or make polygamy legal (though I have no problem with that either - it doesn't infringe on anybodies rights that I can see).<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>I'd like to think I'm not very traditional, but then again I don't want to use a unisex bathroom if I have a choice.</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--><br>
<br>
But what if they made unisex bathrooms for those who choose to use them? As long as they keep the same sex bathrooms for people like you, is that a problem?<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>I wondered what I would think if a minority of the population wanted to do away with all men and women's restrooms and make them all unisex.</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--><br>
<br>
I would think it is wrong as it infringes on others rights. If they want to have a unisex bathroom <!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>in addition</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END--> to men and womens restrooms, than I have no problem with it myself.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>Or if a movement started to make medical alternatives available to allow men to become pregnent and carry a baby to term, along with making insurance carriers provide coverage.</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> <br>
<br>
Depends. They pay the premiums just like everyone else, but then you have the issue of most elective procedures not being covered, so I don't see why any insurance company would be <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>required</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> to cover this.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>What happens when sex change operations are considered normal medical procedure and are covered by insurance? Will society be ruined? Will it be different and will I want to live there?</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--><br>
<br>
Those who have this operation are required to go through some very intense screening and with very good reason - this is a life changing event if ever there were one.<br>
<br>
If we can show that there was a screwup in the genes or chromosomes or whatever, that caused a person to be the wrong sex at birth (and I believe this does occur and will one day be diagnosed with medical procedures rather than psychological testing), then I certainly am all for correcting that problem if the person chooses that course and have no qualms with insurance covering it.<br>
<br>
If a procedure can enable a person to live a happy life and they freely accept whatever risk the procedure entails, then neither I nor anyone else should be able to stand in their way. <br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>If you don't think releasing restrictions on regulations like marriage will not help poligamists or incest supports in our common law system, you are more of an optimist than me. </em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--><br>
<br>
Seriously, if a guy has 5 wives or if a brother and sister get it on (as long as they are not allowed to conceive), how does that effect you? This is the part I don't get about alot of people. I understand their dislike of certain practices, because believe me, there are alot of things people do that I don't like. What I don't understand is the desire to prohibit people from doing those things if it doesn't infringe on your rights.<br>
<br>
What ever happened to the motto &quot;live and let live&quot;?<br>
